ce:section.ce:para:
Further analysis of the Amide I band can provide important information about the protein structure, as it is strongly influenced by the protein's secondary structure. In several publications, the secondary structure of proteins is determined based on the peaks that contribute to the Amide I formation and estimated with peak deconvolution (Liu et al., 2023; Srour et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2022). For both samples, the selection of peak centers was based on the second derivative as illustrated in Fig. 4
                           C and D. The fitting area in both cases was almost complete, resulting in 10 Gaussian curves (Fig. 4A and B). These peaks were assigned to the corresponding secondary structure conformation (Table 2
                           ), according to the results of previous studies (Barth, 2007; El-Sohaimy et al., 2022; Goormaghtigh et al., 1994; Hadnađev et al., 2018; Karabulut et al., 2022; Kong and Yu, 2007; Srour et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2022). As shown in Table 2, β-sheet conformation was the predominant in both samples, followed by β-turn and random coil. However, whole HPI presented higher content of α-helix and lower content of β-sheet than dehulled HPI, which is in agreement with previous results (Shen et al., 2020b). Similar findings regarding the content of secondary structure conformation have been previously reported. In a recent study, FTIR spectra of hemp protein showed that the β-sheet was the predominant conformation (35.8 %), followed by β-turn (32.1 %), α-helix (16.5 %) and random coil (15.6 %) (Xu et al., 2022). Additionally, the circular dichroism spectroscopy results of the hemp protein isolate confirmed the predominance of β-sheet conformation with 42.6 %, followed by random coil with 35.2 % (Karabulut et al., 2022).
